EDA ¶

Understanding the Dataset:¶

There are 17 categories of flower in the dataset. Each flower has 80 consecutive images of a particular category. There are total of 1360 images.

We have got all the images in the jpg folder, we will now manually split the 80 images into 17 categories.

In [28]:
# Classes Present in the Dataset
# classes = ['Daffodil','Snowdrop', 'Lily Valley', 'Bluebell','Crocus', 'Iris', 'Tigerlily', 'Tulip',
# 'Fritillary', 'Sunflower', 'Daisy', 'Colts Foot','Dandelalion', 'Cowslip', 'Buttercup', 'Windflower','Pansy']
In [29]:
# Checking the total jpg files inside the extracted folder
# fnmatch function is used for filename pattern matching
import fnmatch

count = len(fnmatch.filter(os.listdir(extr_dir_path), '*.jpg'))
print('Total files:', count)

Total files: 1360

We are manually mapping class labels, that will be used at later stages while identifying images from the test folder.

In [30]:
class_labels = {0: 'Daffodil', 1: 'Snowdrop', 2: 'Lily Valley', 3: 'Bluebell', 4: 'Crocus', 5: 'Iris', 6: 'Tigerlily', 7: 'Tulip', 8: 'fritillary', 9: 'Sunflower', 10: 'Daisy', 11: 'Colts Foot', 12: 'Dandelalion', 13: 'Cowslip', 14: 'Buttercup', 15: 'Windflower', 16: 'Pansy'}

There are 17 categories of flowers given in a particular order, In this step we will create an output variable that will store the category of each image, We will create a loop that will assign all the 80 consecutive images to a particular class and then other 80 to another class and so on, we are using numpy repeat function to achieve this.

We will use One-Hot Encoding for the conversion of categories as the model will work on numerical values.

In [31]:
# Assigning Categories
classes = [ i for i in range(0,17) ]
y = np.repeat(classes, 80)

# Using one-hot encoding the 17 categories
y = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y, num_classes=17, dtype='float32')

Image Conversion¶

Converting images into numpy arrays is important, as the model accepts inputs in the form of numpy arrays

Also resizing the images to optimum size of 224x224, so that the model trains faster and VGG-16 works on 224x224 images

In [33]:
# Resizing the images and storing them as numpy arrays
images = []
loc = os.path.expanduser(extr_dir_path)

for filename in sorted(os.listdir(loc)):
    
    img = cv2.imread(os.path.join(loc,filename))    
    
    if img is not None:
        # Resizing the image to 224x224
        img = cv2.resize(img, dsize=(224, 224))
        # Changing the colour space to RGB
        img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
        images.append(img)

images = np.asarray(images)

Model Architecture¶

In [37]:
# keeping VGG-16 as base layer (fixed), without its classifier at top
conv_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet',include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))
conv_base.trainable = False

# building sequential model by adding Conv2D, MaxPool2D and other layers
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(conv_base)
model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=(3,3),padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=(3,3),padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2)))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=(3,3),padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=(3,3),padding="same", activation="relu"))
model.add(layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2)))
model.add(layers.Flatten())
# dropping 20% randomly to prevent overfitting
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dense(17, activation='softmax'))

In [39]:
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator (rescale=1./255,
                                    featurewise_std_normalization=True,
                                    zoom_range=0.2, 
                                    rotation_range=90,
                                    width_shift_range=0.2, 
                                    height_shift_range=0.2, 
                                    horizontal_flip=True, 
                                    fill_mode='nearest')

val_datagen = ImageDataGenerator (rescale=1./255, featurewise_std_normalization=True)

train_generator = train_datagen.flow(X_train, y_train, batch_size=32)

val_generator = val_datagen.flow(X_val, y_val, batch_size=32)

Model Compilation and Evaluation ¶

In [40]:
# Creating checkpoint to sabe the best model
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("trained_model/17flowers_vgg.h5", monitor="val_loss", mode="min", save_best_only = True,
                             verbose=1)

# Stop training when a monitored metric has stopped improving
earlystop = EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_loss',  min_delta = 0,  patience = 3, verbose = 1, restore_best_weights = True)

# Reduce learning rate when a metric has stopped improving
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor = 'val_loss', factor = 0.2, patience = 3, verbose = 1, min_delta = 0.0001)

callbacks = [checkpoint, reduce_lr]

batch_size = 32
ntrain = len(X_train)
nval = len(X_val)

# choosing Adam optimizer, also defining loss function and evaluation metrics
model.compile(
    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(epsilon=0.00001),
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

# fitting the model over 50 epochs here
history = model.fit_generator(
    train_generator,
    validation_data=val_generator,
    epochs=50,
    callbacks = callbacks,
    steps_per_epoch = ntrain // batch_size,
    validation_steps = nval // batch_size
)

# Function to read images from the given path and predict the image class
def imagepredict(path):
    img=mpimg.imread(path)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()
    
    # prediction
    img = image.load_img(path, target_size=(224, 224))
    x = image.img_to_array(img)
    x = np.expand_dims(x, axis=0)
    x = x.astype('float32')/255
    pred = np.argmax(model.predict(x))
    print("Predicted Class of the above image is :  {}.".format(class_labels[pred]))

    

# Printing the Prediction Results    
file_names = [f for f in listdir(test_images_path) if isfile(join(test_images_path, f))]
for i in range(0, len(file_names)):
    file = test_images_path + "/" + file_names[i]
    print("\n(",i+1,")")
    print("Filename : {}".format(file_names[i]))
    imagepredict(file)
